On Tue, Mar 11, 2014 at 5:06 AM, Albert Wang <sometime5858@gmail.com> wrote:

> Hello Lach,
>
> Sorry I forgot to check my email yesterday. I had a terrible day so I went
> to bed early, leaving my reading unfinished which is what I'm going to do
> now.
>
> Regarding to the questions in your last email. I'd say cultural identity
> is a big part of the difference and it sometimes prevents you from engaging
> in the classroom the same way native students do. An alien identity, as I
> find, can always lower you self-esteem in a way that when you are not doing
> as good in your subject, you question yourself as being disadvantaged and
> wonder if you ever would become better. Nay, more, when it comes to moments
> of achievements, you regard that as stroke of luck or will think that
> people are doing quite the same as good you did. Both ways you are
> underestimating you own capability, which in return will quench your
> motivation to make effort and study. Language being another big part of the
> problem for children to involve in their education, I don't see it that big
> of a problem, at least for some under 12 yo. Psychologically it's
> researched that children under age of 12 have all the language acquiring
> equipment of their mind in the best state and can somehow learn the
> language from their environment the same way native born children do (also
> this leads to oblivion of their first acquired language during infant
> period with lack of practice). For children above that age, this issue can
> become complicated. Whether they can figure out a way to faster cope with
> the environment and acquire efficiently all necessary language skills to
> learn in a class room scenario can be crucial a thing. But then again, I
> think most of students can figure a way out. It's how much time they take
> that varies among individuals. Children with sufficient skill to cope with
> environment thereby requires more attention from their teacher for sure.
> Another thing is a friendly social environment for them to practice and
> support from family and friends (along with help of course).
>
> There's no need to raise up the idea of proximal learning zone again so I
> think I'll just state my idea here. Getting along with a shifted
> environment, as I just said, takes time. The more different an environment
> they are thrown into, the more terrifying it could be. So teacher has to
> learn more of students varied backgrounds and at least make them
> comfortable into a new one by taking them in by steps. I think here firstly
> should be the language. Use less complicated syntax and grammar and common
> words for the start. Bring them in able to understand first, then go on
> with the more difficult ones. This is particularly crucial for foreign
> language speaking students to cope in. Then help them on knowledge of
> social customs and culture. Tell them how to make friends. All the to-dos
> and not-to-dos. Ask their questions on why people do some things they never
> thought should be necessary. As it's clear you can't expect their parents
> to tell them the same things as they are likely to be foreign language
> speaking too in this case.
>
> A whole other big part of obstacle for this group of students, as far as I
> concern, is their culture itself. This is absolutely more the case for
> students with Asian background (or African background of course lol). They
> are not similar and as I personally come from an Asian background and not
> completely familiar with African one, I'll just talk about it on the level
> of Asian background difference. Almost all northeast asian counties and
> many of the southeasts, their cultures are interdependent. This means they
> tend to think of themselves as around average and see more ways themselves
> as similar or the same with others, as opposed to most western cultures. So
> try to forge the idea of individual difference into their mind and
> encourage them to stand out and be different from others. And also an
> interdependent tradition makes them particularly in need for a social
> circle and friendly environment to knock in. These children seem more
> likely to feel alone and isolated and pretty fragile in their mental
> states.
>
> But after all, I always tend to think of people, especially children and
> adolescents about school age, as in possession of great flexibility and
> potentiality, and therefore and always adjust themselves according to their
> environment. So guidance and help are more of what they need than teaching
> and imparting after all. Also there are so many things to talk about on
> this topic that I can't all cover in one short email. We can discuss on it
> more later. In terms of any further question, send me an email and I'll try
> my best to help.
>
> Albert
>
>
